{{Infobox organization | name = High Pay Centre | type = Think tank | registration_id = Company Registration (England and Wales) No. 07891638 | status = Private Limited by Guarantee | purpose = | headquarters = London | leader_title = Executive Director | leader_name = Luke Hildyard | leader_title2 = Chair | leader_name2 = Nick Isles | leader_title3 = | leader_name3 = | leader_title4 = | leader_name4 = | revenue = £94,239 | revenue_year = 2016 | disbursements = | expenses = £94,239 | expenses_year = 2016 | endowment = | endowment_year = | staff = 1.5 | staff_year = 2016 | volunteers = | volunteers_year = | website = <!-- {{URL|http://highpaycentre.org}} --> | remarks = | formerly = | footnotes = }}
The '''High Pay Centre''' is a [[United Kingdom|UK]] [[think tank]] carrying out [[research]] and analysis on issues relating to top [[income]]s, [[corporate governance]], and [[business performance management|business performance]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highpaycentre.org/about|title=About - High Pay Centre|website=Highpaycentre.org|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> The Centre is generally critical of existing top pay practices, and advocates policies designed to reduce [[economic inequality]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highpaycentre.org/pubs/reform-agenda-how-to-make-top-pay-fairer|title=Reform Agenda: How to make top pay fairer - Publications - High Pay Centre|website=Highpaycentre.org|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> HPC research and commentary on high pay and [[pay inequities|inequality]] are regularly cited in the [[UK media]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highpaycentre.org/press|title=Press - High Pay Centre|website=Highpaycentre.org|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref>
Since 2014, the Centre has promoted 'fatcat day', usually occurring in the first week of January, marking the date on which the earnings for the average FTSE 100 Chief Executive surpasses the amount that the average UK worker can expect to earn all year.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/business/2018/jan/04/fat-cat-thursday-top-bosses-earn-workers-annual-salary-by-lunchtime</ref>
The Centre was established by [[Compass (think tank)|Compass]] in 2009 as the High Pay Commission, and changed its name to the High Pay Centre following publication of the final report of the Commission.<ref>https://www.compassonline.org.uk/action/campaigns/high-pay-commission-for-a-just-and-sustainable-economy/</ref>
Funders for project work during 2018 include [[Joseph Rowntree Charitable Trust]] (£50,000) and [[Chartered Institute of Personnel and Development]] (£25,000).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://highpaycentre.org/about/faq |title=High Pay Centre - FAQs |publisher=High Pay Centre |accessdate=10 June 2018}}</ref>
